        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The ^12CO(2-1) molecular gas content of NGC 2110 will be mapped with ALMA's Band 6 centered at 230.538 GHz (bandwidth 125 MHz). To achieve maximum sensitivity, we will use a channel spacing of 15.625MHz, corresponding to a spectral resolution of 2 x 20.3 = 40.6 km/s. This should be ample to resolve the line, whose width has been estimated to be 355 km/s (Maiolino et al. 1997), and lead to an accurate kinematical map of the molecular gas, which we expect to be associated with the (spatially extended) high extinction area shown in Figure 2.

To achieve the maximum possible spatial resolution (0.18 arcsec), we request the 34 antenna ALMA array to be arranged in the most extended baseline. The corresponding maximum scale, 3.7 arcsec, should easily encompass the molecular gas distribution (Figure 2).

Since no ^12CO(2-1) data exist for NGC 2110, we rely on the
^12CO(1-0) NRAO 12m data of Maiolino et al. (1997) to estimate the exposure times required for the observations. The authors measured a line flux of 0.45 K km/s on the T_R scale, a
full-width-half-maximum of 355 km/s and a central wavelength of
2330 km/s. The 12m dish size used in Maiolino et al.'s
observations corresponds to a beam size at 230 GHz (=0.001304m) of 1.22 x (0.001304m/12m) = 0.00013 rad = 27.35 arcsec. If we
assume that the flux is distributed in a region 2 arcsec across (i.e. across the high extinction area shown in Figure 2), and if we further assume (for lack of better data) that the ^12CO(2-1) and ^12CO(1-0) line fluxes are equal, line intensity at ALMA is then equal to 0.45 K km/s x (27.35 / 2.0)^2 / 355 km/s = 0.24 K. Using this value in ALMA's on-line Sensitivity calculator gives an exposure time of 20 minute (1 sigma).</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
