    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>High-resolution observations in the near infrared show a 10 pc cylindrical region of dust around the active galactic nucleus (AGN) of the Seyfert 1 NGC2110, along with a 35 pc ring of star clusters. These are seen for the first time in our imaging and gas kinematics of the central 100pc with the Keck OSIRIS instrument with adaptive optics. The regional formation rate (SFR) is 0.3 M_sun/yr. The gas dynamics imply a super-massive black hole of 3-4 x 10^8 MâŠ™. With ALMA we propose to observe the CO associated with the dust cylinder (or torus) and learn its kinematics and physical state. </prp:abstract>
